'''Faithbooking''', or '''spiritual [[scrapbooking]]''' is a creative expression of a family's spiritual journey, values and events that are captured in [[Scrapbooking|scrapbook]]s, [[Diary|diaries]] or [[Diary|journals]] that combine the use of photographs, decorated papers, scripture, thoughts, prayers, blessings, stories and embellishments such as buttons, ribbon and other creative art media.<ref>{{cite book |title=100 Creative Activities for Sabbath |last=Holford |first=Karen |year=2006 |publisher=Pacific Press Publishing |isbn=0-8163-2139-6 |pages=106 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h0iVwSxKDNcC&pg=PA106&dq=Faithbooking&client=firefox-a&sig=MhCgK9qRrMI4rR1G1qeHfobZlGk }}</ref> The goal of faithbooking is to creatively preserve and tell a story about how a family grows spiritually.<ref>{{cite book |title=The therapist's notebook for integrating spirituality in counseling |last=Helmeke |first=Karen B. |author2=Sori, Catherine Ford |year=2006 |publisher=Haworth Press |isbn=0-7890-2991-X |pages=214 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UsqVAF2FYfMC&pg=PA214&dq=Faithbooking&client=firefox-a&sig=iAmmEZvCquk8jLCvR90dCGhXUN8#PPA214,M1 }}</ref> Many religions such as [[Christianity]], [[Judaism]] and [[Islam]] have adopted the concept of faithbooking.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}

